Enabling ConnectWise (Employee Version)

 

Given all the phishing activity lately, you may be skeptical of this request, but rest assured this is a legitimate request of Stairsupplies IT. If you still have doubts, reach out to the IT department for verification.

StairSupplies is moving to new remote management software. There are limitations that prevent fully automatic installs of this software on Macs.

On Tuesday, you received a popup similar to this:

You will need to manually grant the software the permissions it requires. The following steps will walk you through that process.

 

Granting Accessibility Access

Under Accessibility on the right pane, click the button Request Access...

This will bring you into System Preferences > Accessibility. In the right pane under Allow the apps below to control your computer click the empty check box to the left of connectwisecon...

Once done, it will look like this:

 

Granting Screen Recording Access

Due to a bug in the ConnectWise software, clicking Request Access... like done previous doesn't populate the right pane with the ConnectWise process. We will have to do this manually.

While still in System Preferences > Accessibility, right click connectwisecon... and select Show in Finder. This will launch a Finder window bringing you to where the ConnectWise executable is stored in /opt/. Now click Screen Recording in System Preferences.

In Finder, drag the connectwisecontrol icon into the blank space on the right pane of System Preferences:

You may see a popup instructing you quit ConnectWise to use the application. It doesn't matter which option you select.

 

ConnectWise should now have its check box checked in both Accessibility and Screen Recording, and the ConnectWise popup should now look like this:

This popup times out after some time, so if it's nowhere to be found then that means permissions have been successfully granted.
